      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nLet us begin this text with a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Do It Yourself</b><br /><br />Imagine you were tasked with designing a new structure where people at the top could be seen and heard by everyone below. Additionally, your design must also impress those who visit it.<br /><br />Given this description, what kind of structure would you create?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "This same question likely arose among many ancient civilizations. In this text, we will explore how they had all the necessary means to answer it.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_begin",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Beginning\n\nImmediately responding to the idea of building something tall and occupying a large space is tempting. However, in nature, structures always begin from the smallest possible forms. For this reason, we will first examine smaller structures.\n\n#### The People’s House\n\nIn different cultures, when buildings survive for long periods—even after the people who once dominated a region have left—they are generally made of durable materials like stone. On the other hand, structures built by ordinary people often use softer materials, frequently taken directly from trees, as was common in the Americas (*Abya Yala*). These materials deteriorate more easily over time due to natural events like rain. An example can be seen in **Figure 1**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"miPueblito\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('miPueblito', '0%')\" src=\"images/MiPueblito/MiPueblito.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: Indigenous buildings in <i>Mi Pueblito</i>, Panama. Photo taken on <htdate0> during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "1",
                     "day": "17"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The buildings in *Mi Pueblito* have all the geometric shapes we have studied so far. At the top, we see a triangular form, but since it is not drawn on a flat plane, we call it a prism. On the walls, we observe rectangular wooden boards placed side by side.\n\nWe can conclude that constructing these buildings required at least the following steps:\n- Placing the wood, one piece at a time, in its final position. In other words, the indigenous people added wooden pieces until they achieved the final result: the building.\n- The repetitive process of placing wood is also related to multiplication, though we usually associate this method only with addition.\n- The triangular slope of the roofs likely emerged from observing nature, as this shape allows water to flow off, preventing pooling.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Whether the indigenous people intentionally used mathematics or simply replicated natural patterns, both addition and multiplication are directly linked to natural phenomena—and, consequently, to human actions\n\n#### Conservation\nStructures like those in **Figure 1** are only preserved for long periods when extreme natural events occur. One such event—a volcanic eruption—took place in Joya de Cerén, El Salvador, and is responsible for preserving the buildings in **Figure 2** to this day",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "21315015-e589-486f-b0aa-3eba1d775b1d",
                     "text": "Ministerio de Cultura, El Salvador",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"JC\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('JC', '0%')\" src=\"images/JoyaCeren/JoyaCeren.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 2: Indigenous buildings in <i>Joya de Ceren</i>, El Salvador. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "24"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_south",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Numbers and Great Works\n\nAs our knowledge advances, it is expected that humanity will achieve increasingly significant—and consequently more visible—results. In this section, we revisit the case of Caral, Peru.\n\n#### The Numbers\nUpon visiting the archaeological site of Caral, we encounter the panel displayed in **Figure 3**, which mentions the discovery of a *quipu* in the city",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c2ff41fc-7833-4dc2-8882-eaed12a065b7",
                     "text": "Mann, Charles C., pp. 1008",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2005",
                        "month": "6",
                        "day": "26"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"qp\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('qp', '0%')\" src=\"images/Caral/QuipuPanel.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figura 3: Panel at the archaeological site of Caral. © ZonaArqueólogicaCaral (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('720f6dfd-4b86-4e07-a887-1010e1041a4d'); return false;\">Ruta Caral, <htdate0></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('03c3743c-d268-4730-ba8e-d36b5c49e781'); return false;\">Youtube - Caral Perú Oficial, <htdate1></a>). Photo taken on <htdate2>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "1",
                     "day": "17"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "1",
                     "day": "17"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2017",
                     "month": "5",
                     "day": "31"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "As discussed in other *History Tracers* articles, *quipus* were initially understood as a counting system, but recent studies suggest they may have encoded more complex information",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2ebd3420-941b-4f17-b5bc-17bb39ef37a0",
                     "text": "Hyland, S.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "11",
                        "day": "7"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b74bf294-c758-4a48-88c9-399ca4f021f6",
                     "text": "Cartwright, M.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "8"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75ca7e93-6ffd-4303-b21d-b669592dcde3",
                     "text": "Urton, G.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2019",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Constructions\n\nSimilarly, the indigenous people’s grasp of mathematics is evident in their architecture. They created scaled-down models of their structures before construction, meaning they identified the proportional factors required for enlargement. As a result, they erected monuments like the one shown in **Figure 4**",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3b18a263-71e9-4c61-a7fe-c23cbce65624",
                     "text": "Zona Caral",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "9",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b9af756b-558a-4292-b71b-d9b3cc47d570",
                     "text": "de la Morena, Raquel",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"CaralH1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CaralH1', '0%')\" src=\"images/Caral/CaralPiramideH1.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 4: The H1 Pyramid at the archaeological site of Caral. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2017",
                     "month": "5",
                     "day": "31"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To conclude this section on Andean civilizations, we highlight the mountain behind the H1 Pyramid in **Figure 4**. Caral’s pyramidal complex dates back over four thousand years and, like Machu Picchu’s structures—analyzed in a previous article—exhibits forms that mirror natural landscapes (wide bases narrowing toward the top). If Caral’s *quipus* functioned similarly to those of the Incas, we might be looking at a millennia-old system of knowledge preservation.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_north",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Mesoamericans\n\nIn the American (*Abya Yala*) continent, alongside the Indigenous peoples of the Andes, we also find monumental constructions among Mesoamerican civilizations, who developed a vigesimal (base-20) numerical system",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d1b7daa6-a743-4a66-9cfe-ff4286868f35",
                     "text": "Hernández Mendoza, Aurelio & Pérez López, Felipa",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                     "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga, pp. 34 - 36, 119 - 174",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Copán Images\n\nA panel at Copán, shown in **Figure 5**, has been referenced in multiple studies:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Temple16Copan.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 5: Panel at the archaeological site of Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1>, during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "This panel shows the 9 building steps of the Temple 16 in Copan. We can observe after the three small building steps, the fourth step is a big basis for the next steps. Among all steps, it is highlighted the Rosalila, with their multiple entrances and an space on top for somebody communicate with population.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "As illustrated in **Figure 5**, successive structures were built atop one another, culminating in the current form of Temple 16 at Copán. Visitors to the site can enter the temple and observe a chamber separating the Rosalila phase from later construction stages (12th–15th rulers)",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple2', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Templo16Inside.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:40%;\"/>Figure 6: Interior view of Temple 16 at Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1> during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "Another view of Temple 16, we observe a hall doing transition between consecutive steps of Figura 1.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Finally, we include an exterior view of Temple 16:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple3', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Temple16External.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:40%;\"/>Figure 7: Exterior view of Temple 16 at Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1>, during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Multiplication in Superposition\n\n**Figure 7** shows stones placed (added) side by side. The repetition of such patterns allows grouping—a tangible representation of multiplication in architecture.\n\nThe layered construction in **Figure 5** further reflects multiplicative principles. For clarity, refer to **Chart 1**, plotting the first five multiplication tables:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart4\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Points from multiplication tables 1–5 connected by lines. Chart generated with <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "When we move from one multiplication table to another—keeping the value being multiplied along the horizontal axis—we observe that the values in the table, represented on the vertical axis, move farther from the horizontal line. When these points are connected, they form a triangular shape.\n\nBy comparing **Figure 5** with **Chart 1**, we can identify that the steps on the left side and the last two steps of the structure on the right have inclinations consistent with the drawn charts. If a ladder appears excessively inclined, this simply indicates a need to adjust the table values to more closely match what is observed.\n\n#### Did the Mesoamerican people multiply?\n\nBefore answering this question, it is important to better contextualize the region. Figure 8 presents a map of the northern region of the American (*Abya Yala*) continent. On the left side of the continent lies an extensive mountainous region, which includes a large portion of Honduras, where Copán is located:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/mapswire/continent_na-physical-map-north-america-robinson-269.jpg\" id=\"imgMoutains\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMoutains', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 8: Mountain ranges of northern America (Abya Yala) continent. © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Mountains—abundant in Mesoamerica, as in the Andes—provided both inspiration and the logic for construction.\n\nDr. Ximena Catepillán notes that while no records confirm the Maya’s extensive use of mathematics, evidence suggests they employed grid-based multiplication",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9e7d0cea-d968-4bd5-886e-bc08c824e7ca",
                     "text": "Díaz, Ruy D.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2006",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "A future text will detail Maya arithmetic methods. For now, we summarize: Numbers were placed outside grids, multiplied, and results positioned inside. Diagonal sums yielded final answers, adjusted to prevent values exceeding 19 per positional digit",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9e7d0cea-d968-4bd5-886e-bc08c824e7ca",
                     "text": "Díaz, Ruy D.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2006",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "For example, let us multiply 4 × 3 = 12 using this method",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
